  "market_context": "Gold is trading within an hourly consolidation range where the upper high has already been taken out while the range low remains intact. A reversal candle forms with a wick, and the analyst evaluates whether price will respect 50% of that wick to trade lower, noting the consolidation context lowers the probability of upside continuation.",
  "key_observation": "On the 5-minute time frame, price opens and immediately falls through the 50% level of the hourly wick rather than respecting it. This disrespect of the mean threshold means an expansion candle higher is unlikely, and price is more probable to take out the consolidation low instead.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify that gold on the hourly is in a consolidation range, with the range high already swept but the range low still intact.",
    "Step 2: Note a reversal candle with a clean wick forming, and acknowledge that while it could suggest higher movement, the consolidation context makes that lower probability.",
    "Step 3: Confirm price has closed back inside the previous candle's range and set the expectation that 0.5 of the wick must hold for a bullish expansion.",
    "Step 4: Drop down to the 5-minute time frame to observe how price reacts at the 50% wick level.",
    "Step 5: Observe that as price opens, it immediately trades lower and falls through 50% of the wick, disrespecting the mean threshold.",
    "Step 6: Conclude that an expansion candle higher is not feasible without forming an oversized wick, so the consolidation low is the more likely draw on liquidity.",
    "Step 7: Confirm the thesis as price expands lower and takes out the consolidation low."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price expanded lower and swept the consolidation low as anticipated, validating the wick-disrespect read.",
  "lessons": "When price fails to respect 50% of a reversal wick on the lower time frame, expansion in that direction is invalidated. Combined with consolidation context where the opposing range extreme is untouched, the untaken liquidity becomes the highest-probability draw.",
